                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 37.—<hi rend="italic">Ulceration of toes.</hi>—<name type="person" key="599">Private Israel J.
                                                Gromoble</name>, <name type="organization" key="643">Co. I, 148th Pa.</name>; age 18; was admitted <date type="transfer" when="1863-09-23">Sept. 23,
                                                1863</date>, from <name type="hospital" key="152">Finley hospital</name>, Washington, D. C, as a
                                        convalescent from typhoid fever. On <date type="injury" when="1863-09-26">the 26th</date> four of the
                                        patient's toes were found to be ulcerated and much
                                        congested. Incisions were made around the ulcers and
                                        warm-water dressings prescribed, with tincture of iron
                                        internally, porter and extra diet; a wash containing sugar
                                        of lead and opium and an alcohol and water lotion were
                                        subsequently employed. On October 18 the ulcers were
                                        granulating. All treatment was omitted on the 25th, and on
                                                <date type="duty" when="1863-11-16">November
                                                16</date> the patient was returned to
                                                duty.—<hi rend="italic"><name type="hospital">Mower Hospital,
                                                        Philadelphia, Pa.</name></hi>
                                </p>
                        
